  "prompt": "Why is a crush called a crush?",
  "response": "The term \"crush\" to describe a strong attraction or infatuation towards someone has a somewhat unclear origin, but it gained popularity in the late 19th century. One commonly accepted theory is that it refers to the overwhelming feelings that can \"crush\" a person emotionally when they are smitten with someone. \n\nAnother possible explanation is tied to the idea of youthful or fleeting love\u2014often experienced during adolescence\u2014where the feelings can be intense but not necessarily deep or long-lasting. The term may also reflect the notion of being \"crushed\" by the intensity of these feelings, which can be both exhilarating and overwhelming.\n\nOverall, while the exact origins are not definitively known, the metaphorical use of \"crush\" effectively captures the experience of intense infatuation.",
